		<div class="post" id="post-4432177">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,4432177)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-4432177">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/djkaktus" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1888434); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1888434&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610198384" alt="djkaktus" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1888434)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/djkaktus" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1888434); return false;" >djkaktus</a></span> <span class="odate time_1574774880 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">26 Nov 2019 13:28</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4432177">
									

<blockquote>
<p>I wonder what the site would look like if it were just authors posting for the love of the craft and medium instead.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>It is perhaps presumptive of you, someone who has had such a seemingly unhealthy relationship with this website, to decry authors on this website for <em>not</em> posting for the love of the craft and medium, as if you somehow know their intentions and motivations. Frankly, there are few people I would trust <em>less</em> with that call than someone with such an unfortunately altered view of reality.</p>
<p>That said, you're certainly free to your opinion, although I'd warn against expecting anyone to take you seriously. Criticizing a community of people, calling their efforts a <em>feeding frenzy</em> as if they were sharks with blood in the water, while being wholly incapable of interacting with that community in any substantive way for more than a few weeks at a time, is disingenuous at best.</p>
<p>There are dozens of people I interact with every day who are happy to work on their projects, whether those projects are written efforts or staff work, and couldn't give an ass and a half about whether they ever get any upvotes. People happy to contribute and collaborate with this community in healthy, productive ways. <strong>In fact</strong>, I'd argue that most people I interact with here on a daily basis have happy, productive relationships with the wiki. Presuming to know their minds while barely ever engaging with them outside of passive aggressive criticism on <em>yet another account</em> is laughable.</p>
<p>In short, please do not presume that your hangups with this place are everybody's hangups with this place. Your issues are not universal.</p>
<p>tl;dr: I'm not mad, I'm just disappointed.</p>
<p>Edit:</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Disclaimer:&nbsp;Clarification&nbsp;of&nbsp;Intent</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>The SCP Foundation Criticism Policy's first rule indicates that reviewers should &quot;Critique the work, not the author [sic]&quot;. However, by turning their author page into a personal manifesto the author has made it impossible to critique this work without also critiquing the author, if honest intent can be assumed. The author has used this page to espouse personal, seemingly deeply held views and any critique on the writing outside of basic spelling, grammar and format must be critical of those views. As such, for the sake of ease of address I have used the words &quot;you&quot; and &quot;your&quot; to address the spoken voice of the manifesto, which can be assumed by any rational reviewer to be the same as the author.</p>
<p>In any such case that a reader finds offense in the use of these terms intended to simplify address, the reader is free to substitute &quot;the intended voice of this manifesto&quot; in the place of the applicable possessive pronouns.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

